, England, United Kingdom","Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Quemeford Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Quemerford, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Billet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hadassa, Herschel, Mendel, Mertie.","French: from a shortened form of <i>Robillet</i>, itself a pet form of   Robert  .","French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bille</i> ‘block, piece of tree trunk; stick’ (see   Bille  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Billett","meanings":["English: variant of   Billet  .","Possibly also an altered form of French   Billet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Billiet","meanings":["French: variant of   Billet  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Billet was born in 1350, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Bellot, was 28 and his mother, Lady Robert Bellot, was 22. He married Mrs. William Billet about 1368, in Calne, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1350–":"1350–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1385–1473":"1385–1473","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1385":"1385","1473":"1473","about 1368":"umbes 1368","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","Thorp, Gayton, Norfolk, England":"Gayton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calne, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Quemeford Caine Wiltshire England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Quemerford, Calne, Wiltshire, England":"Calne, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1350–":"1350–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1385–1473":"1385–1473","1322–Male":"1322–Kuollut","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1385":"1385","1473":"1473","about 1368":"noin 1368","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1328":"1328","Thorp, Gayton, Norfolk, England":"Gayton, Norfol